Certainly! Here's an example MATLAB code that measures the fundamental period of a signal over a specified time window using autocorrelation:

```matlab
% Input signal
signal = [1 2 3 4 1 2 3 4];

% Time window parameters
window_start = 1;    % Start index of time window
window_end = 4;      % End index of time window

% Extract time window from signal
time_window = signal(window_start:window_end);

% Compute autocorrelation
autocorr = xcorr(time_window);

% Find the first peak after the central value
[~, peaks] = findpeaks(autocorr);
fundamental_period = peaks(1);

% Print the fundamental period
disp(['Fundamental period: ' num2str(fundamental_period)]);
```

In this code, the signal is a 1-dimensional array. You can modify the `signal` variable to represent your own input signal. The `window_start` and `window_end` variables determine the range of the time window you want to analyze.

The code calculates the autocorrelation of the time window using the `xcorr` function. Then, it identifies the first peak in the autocorrelation function after the central value using the `findpeaks` function. The peak value corresponds to the fundamental period of the signal.

Finally, the code prints the fundamental period.

