Certainly! Here's the modified code that measures the fundamental period of each time window using Fourier analysis:

```matlab
% Input signal
signal = [1 2 3 4 1 2 3 4];

% Time window parameters
window_size = 4;    % Size of time window

% Preallocate arrays for storing results
fundamental_periods = zeros(1, length(signal) - window_size + 1);
window_indices = zeros(1, length(signal) - window_size + 1);

% Iterate over time windows
num_windows = length(signal) - window_size + 1;
for i = 1:num_windows
    % Extract time window from signal
    window_start = i;
    window_end = i + window_size - 1;
    time_window = signal(window_start:window_end);

    % Compute Fourier transform
    f = fft(time_window);

    % Find frequency components
    P2 = abs(f/window_size);
    P1 = P2(1:window_size/2+1);
    P1(2:end-1) = 2*P1(2:end-1);

    % Find peak frequency index
    [~, idx] = max(P1);

    % Calculate fundamental period
    sample_rate = 1;
    fundamental_period = 1 / (idx-1) / sample_rate;

    % Store fundamental period and window index
    fundamental_periods(i) = fundamental_period;
    window_indices(i) = window_start;
end

% Plot fundamental period over time
plot(window_indices, fundamental_periods);
xlabel('Window Index');
ylabel('Fundamental Period');
title('Fundamental Period over Time');
```

In this modified version, the code calculates the Fourier transform of each time window using `fft`. Then, it finds the frequency components using the calculated transform. The peak frequency index with the maximum amplitude is determined using `max`. 

The fundamental period is calculated using the sample rate and the index of the maximum frequency component. Finally, the fundamental periods and window indices are stored in the arrays, and the line plot is created using `plot`.

Now, when you run the code, it will compute the fundamental period for each time window using Fourier analysis and plot the results as a line plot.

