```matlab
% Input signal
signal = [1 2 3 4 1 2 3 4];
time_between_points = 0.002; % Time between points in milliseconds

% Window and step size variables
window_size = 4;    % Size of time window
step_size = 2;      % Size of time step

% Preallocate arrays for storing results
fundamental_frequencies = [];
window_indices = [];

% Iterate over time windows with given step size
num_windows = floor((length(signal) - window_size + 1) / step_size);
for i = 1:num_windows
    % Calculate start index of current time window
    window_start = 1 + (i-1)*step_size;

    % Extract time window from signal
    window_end = window_start + window_size - 1;
    time_window = signal(window_start:window_end);

    % Compute Fourier transform
    f = fft(time_window);

    % Find frequency components
    P2 = abs(f/window_size);
    P1 = P2(1:window_size/2+1);
    P1(2:end-1) = 2*P1(2:end-1);

    % Find peak frequency index
    [~, idx] = max(P1);

    % Calculate fundamental frequency in hertz
    fundamental_frequency = 1 / (idx-1) / time_between_points;

    % Store fundamental frequency and window index
    fundamental_frequencies = [fundamental_frequencies fundamental_frequency];
    window_indices = [window_indices window_start];
end

% Plot fundamental frequency over time
plot(window_indices, fundamental_frequencies);
xlabel('Window Index');
ylabel('Fundamental Frequency (Hz)');
title('Fundamental Frequency over Time');
```

In this updated version, I added a variable `time_between_points` to represent the time between points in milliseconds (0.002 ms in this case). The fundamental period is then calculated by taking `1 / (idx-1) / time_between_points`, which converts the reciprocal of the index to Hertz.

